4gh : Citrix VM Upgrade : Linux
This is just a reference. Actual values will differ for the drives and paths

1. Go to the VM.
2. Add another disk from the storage tab. For example, client wants to upgrade from startup tp enterprise, add another 20GB
3. 20GB+20GB=40GB
4. Login to console.

5.Now need to create a primary partition for our NEW disk (see new disk name using # fdisk -l )

6. fdisk /dev/newdisk (put new disk name here, usually /dev/xdb)
i) Give command : # n (add a new partition) » # p (primary partion) » type 1 » Enter (unless it creates partiion)
ii) then give command : # w (write table to disk and exit)

7. pvcreate /dev/newdisk1 (usually /dev/xdb)

8. Now extend vol group. You can see curent vol group using command : # vgdisplay
i) # vgextend NameOfVG /dev/newdisk1 (Usually vg name is : VolGroup)

9. Now extend logical vol group. You can see logical vol group using command : # lvdisplay
i) # lvextend /dev/volgroup/LogVol /dev/newdisk1 (lv name usually /dev/volgroup/LogVol**)

10. # resize2fs /dev/volgroup/LogVol** (To resize the filesystem)
11. Increase the cores and shutdown.
12. Increase the RAM and bootup.
4gh : Citrix VM Upgrade : Windows

1. Go to the VM.
2. Shutdown
3. Expand the disk drive fom the Storage tab.(Do not add new disk, there is option to expand disk for windows VM)
4. Increase the RAM.
5. Increase the number of cores
6. Boot the VM
7. Login to the VM
8. Now to expand disk go to Administrative Tools » Computer Management » Disk Managment » right click on allocated space » click on expand » complete the steps » Finish.

# grep 'addondomain.com' /var/cpanel/users/*	-->> to find a addon domain through cmd

# /usr/local/cpanel/bin/update-roundcube --force	-->> to update roundcube

